story.title: Falco - Episode 10
story.storyDescription: Libby Dixon is missing. Will Agent Falco crack the case?
story.creator: web-uploader
story.prePaywallNotification: 🤔🤔 Libby Dixon wasn’t murdered by someone associated with the sheriff’s office…so then who killed her? Tap back into Hooked to find out.
story.postPaywallNotification: Could Anna Mae Dixon be covering for her ex-boyfriend Jimmy? 🤔 Tap back into Hooked to find out if she is.

messages.text: Investigation: Day 11
The following is a transcript of an interview between Agent Falco and Anna Mae Dixon, recorded June 30, 10:03 AM.
Thanks for coming back in, Anna Mae.
I’d like to ask you a few questions about Jimmy Fitz, if that’s okay.
Why are you asking about Jimmy?
I understand you're very fond of him, aren’t you?
We’re in love.
But he broke up with you, correct?
Yeah, but he always comes back to me.
We’re soulmates.
Did you know that he was seeing someone else?
He doesn’t like anybody else like that.
I know this is painful for you, Anna Mae…
But I regret to inform you that he’d been sleeping with your sister.
No, he wasn’t—
He had nothing to do with what happened to her.
That asshole Duke Simmons murdered my sister.
You’re wasting your time accusing Jimmy of something horrible.
Your sister was six weeks pregnant when she died.
We tested the fetal DNA and ran it through the CODIS database.
It was a match to Jimmy Fitz.
What are you talking about?
Jimmy’s DNA was collected when he was arrested in 2014 for a felony DUI.
His DNA matches the DNA we recovered from your sister’s unborn child.
Jimmy Fitz was the father.
Anna Mae cradles her head in her hands and begins to rock back and forth in her chair.
Stop it. Why are you torturing me like this?
I’m sorry to cause you pain.
But Jimmy’s lawyered up so I can’t talk to him anymore. Can you help me fill in the gaps?
I’m not helping you build a case against him.
Did you have any suspicions that he was romantically involved with your sister?
No, because he wasn’t. Jimmy loves me.
DNA doesn’t lie, Anna Mae.
Then Libby must’ve coerced him into bed or something.
Jimmy was seen checking into the Star 7 motel with Libby.
He went there willingly, didn’t he?
She could’ve gotten him drunk — he drinks too much sometimes.
Maybe he didn’t know what he was doing.
Anna Mae looks up at Agent Falco, her eyes full of tears.
How did Jimmy act after Libby disappeared?
He came over immediately to help me. I was so upset.
Did he say anything suspicious or out of the ordinary to you?
No. I’m not letting you lock Jimmy up for a crime he didn’t commit, okay?
I’m only here because my mom is making me.
You seem pretty defensive of Jimmy.
If you’re covering for him, that could be obstruction of justice.
And if you helped him hide the evidence, that makes you an accessory after the fact.
This man cheated on you with your sister, Anna Mae:
He committed statutory rape by having sex with a minor.
He got her pregnant and then he murdered her to keep her quiet when she wouldn’t get an abortion.
Anna Mae slams her open palm down on the table.
No, he didn’t!
Stop covering for him.
I’m not covering for Jimmy — he’s innocent.
Okay. Are those Gucci sunglasses?
Yeah.
I got them for Christmas last year.
You look a lot like Libby, don’t you, Anna Mae?
Anna Mae shifts in her seat as Agent Falco leans in closer.
What?
Same long brown hair.
About the same height.
Same hourglass shape.
You’re what — 140 pounds?
Anna Mae pulls her cardigan together at the middle and crosses her legs.
Why are you asking about my weight?
Have you ever been to Newbury?
Yeah, who hasn’t?
The clerk at the Wired cafe saw you, Anna Mae.
Yeah, so?
I’ve been receiving some threatening Facespace messages from a fake account.
Does the name “Connor Mason” mean anything to you?
Anna Mae looks down at her sneakers.
I don’t know what you’re talking about.
I didn’t send any threatening messages from a Wired computer.
But we know you did. We traced the IP address to that location.
The clerk verified seeing you there when the messages were sent.
I know you tried to scare me off the case to protect Jimmy.
But you have to let him go.
You will live in guilt if you choose a boy over your own dead sister.
How would Libby feel if she knew you protected her killer?
There’s a pause before Agent Falco speaks again, quietly this time.
He doesn’t even love you, Anna Mae.
He cheated on you.
Listen to the facts — he dumped you for your own flesh and blood.
Anna Mae jumps up suddenly and pushes the table away from her.
Stop it! Please, stop.
He will be arrested, whether you help us or not, Anna Mae.
He will rot in a cell for your sister’s murder.
Shut up!
Jimmy didn’t kill Libby, okay?
I did — I killed her.
But it was an accident.
Jimmy wasn’t even there when she died.
How can I believe you?
Are you confessing to his crime to protect him?
No. I knew Jimmy dumped me for someone new.
I could see it in his eyes — he was falling for someone else.
Anna Mae paces back and forth across the interview room, frantic.
I just wanted to know who.
So I went to his work and hid a tracking device under his truck.
When?
On June 16.
I ordered it online and that’s when it came.
But he didn’t go anywhere suspicious ‘til the 18th.
The device said he was at The Junction, so I knew he was hooking up with someone.
I went out there myself.
I had to see who she was.
His truck was in the parking lot…
But I never expected to see Libby’s car there, too.
I couldn’t believe it. I felt like my blood was boiling—
And I wanted to get back at her.
So I snapped some photos of the motel with her car in the lot.
I waited for her to come out so I’d have more proof.
I knew I could show the photos to my dad—
He’d kick Libby out of the house for having sex.
I knew she’d never admit she was with Jimmy…
Because he’d get in too much trouble.
So then I’d have him all to myself again.
What happened next?
Jimmy left the motel first.
I crouched down in my seat, so he didn’t see me.
I wanted to wait to get the photos of Libby — not him.
You punctured her tire, didn’t you?
Yeah, but not at the motel. I wanted to see where she’d go next—
If she’d meet up with Jimmy again somewhere.
So I followed her on Route 12.
Did you flag her down?
No. She stopped by Exit 66.
I tried to keep a safe distance, but she saw my car.
She knew I was following her — so she pulled over to talk to me.
She begged me not to tell our dad — she was crying and carrying on…
But I was just so mad.
Did she tell you she was pregnant?
No, I swear. I had no idea about that.
So the two of you engaged in a verbal altercation over Jimmy?
We were arguing, yeah.
She said she and Jimmy were in love.
I couldn’t take it, I couldn’t. So I grabbed her arm and her bracelet broke.
I shoved her, hard.
She fell back and hit her head on the pavement.
She stopped moving.
But she wasn’t bleeding.
I didn’t mean to hurt her, really.
Not physically.
But you didn’t call 911.
I took CPR and first aid when I was a lifeguard for a summer.
I tried to revive her — I swear.
But she had no pulse. She was dead.
I killed my sister.
Anna Mae suddenly stops pacing and puts her hand over her mouth, choking back a sob.
I knew I’d get in trouble, so I had to do something with her body.
How did you get her to Stark’s Quarry?
I pulled her into the backseat of my car—
She was so heavy.
I drove to the quarry ‘cause I knew it was abandoned.
I stopped at the side of the road and pulled her back out.
Then I dragged her body to the lake and threw her in.
When did you puncture her tire?
Before I went to the quarry.
I keep mace and a pocket knife in my glovebox for protection.
I cut her tire with my knife so you’d think she pulled over for a flat.
I knew she’d look like a runaway, or maybe…
You’d think Duke did something to her.
Then I went home before my mom came back from Greenwald’s. She didn’t think I’d ever left.
Okay. So you sent me threatening messages because you didn’t want me to dig into Libby’s disappearance?
Well, yeah. I knew my dad really pressed for the TBI to help find Libby.
And when you got here, you kept asking too many questions.
I couldn’t let you know the truth — I’d be ruined.
The whole town already thinks I’m a psycho.
I heard Jimmy’s friends talking about me at the diner.
They called me “Psycho Ex.” It’s not fair.
What do you mean?
I can’t take it, living under my father’s roof.
I have no privacy.
He snoops through my phone.
I have no bedroom door.
I’m nineteen and my curfew’s nine o’clock.
For the past six months, I’ve been saving up to move out.
I wanted a new life — just me and Jimmy.
We talked about getting an apartment together.
But Libby took him away from me.
She stole my boyfriend!
And she had sex before marriage.
He got her pregnant, for Pete’s sake.
She’s a minor and he could go to jail for having sex with her.
And they did all of those things on purpose…
But what I did was an accident.
I didn’t mean to hurt her.
I just meant to follow her — to get her in trouble.
I just wanted some answers.
Everybody involved in this made mistakes —
But I’m the “psycho” because I love a man who keeps doing me wrong.
I was afraid — desperate—
Reckless.
But I’m not crazy.
I know. Sometimes our happiness gets wrapped up in other people…
And it hurts when they leave us.
Women are called “crazy” too much for simply having emotions, aren’t we?
But that’s different from “insanity”—
That’s a concept that the legal system uses to absolve a defendant with a mental illness of responsibility for her actions…
What?
Why are you telling me this?
The law can’t lay blame on someone who experiences delusions or hallucinations…
Or doesn’t know right from wrong.
I’m not seeing things, okay?!
Okay, Anna Mae.
You do know right from wrong, though, don’t you?
Of course I do. I told you—
Libby’s death was an accident.
I know you don’t believe me, but it was. I didn’t mean to kill her.
She was my little sister—
It was an accident.
I do believe you, Anna Mae.
It was an accident.
Anna Mae collapses to the floor, black streaks of mascara staining her cheeks as she dissolves into tears.
It was an accident.
It was an accident.
The following is an audio call from Director Philomena Todd to Agent Falco, placed August 1, 9:17 AM.
Falco.
Frankie, its Philomena Todd. Congratulations for closing the Dixon case. Excellent work, Agent.
Thank you, Director. It was a team effort between me and Deputy Decker.
The Cedar Creek DA intends to indict Anna Mae Dixon on charges of second-degree murder—
He doesn’t believe that Libby’s death was really an accident.
But he’s prepared to offer her a deal to avoid putting the family through a trial—
Her poor parents have been through the ringer.
Yeah, I think that’s probably a good idea, to be honest.
I agree. Okay, well, I’m gonna need you back in Nashville as soon as possible—
A three-year old boy was abducted this morning from a crowded bus station downtown. I need you on it with Agent Lopez.
Okay, I’ll be checking out in about an hour, Director.
Excellent. I’ll see you in my office this afternoon for debriefing.
Director?
Yes?
I’d like to recommend Deputy Decker to take over for Agent Kennedy when he retires this September.
You looking for a partner, Agent Falco?
We work well together.
I’ll be in contact with him and take it into consideration.
Thanks, Director.
You’re welcome, Frankie. See you soon.
Okay.
Buh-bye.
Case Resolution Notes:
Anna Mae Dixon was indicted on charges of second-degree murder by the Cedar Creek District Attorney.
She accepted a plea deal on the lesser charge of reckless homicide — a class D felony—
And was sentenced to community service, five years probation, and mandatory outpatient counseling.
The judge called her a “very lucky young lady.”
Jimmy Fitz pled guilty to statutory rape — a class E felony — and was sentenced to two years in prison.
He was ordered to pay a fine of $2500 and register as a sex offender.
Deputy Tex Decker was hired by the Tennessee Bureau of Investigation when Agent Kennedy retired in September.
He successfully completed his field training and is now a Special Agent, working in tandem with Agent Falco.
Libby Dixon was buried in the cemetery next to her father’s church.
Her tombstone was chosen by her father, Darrence Dixon.
Her epitaph reads, “The light shines in the darkness, and the darkness has not overcome it.” —John 1:5.
The following is a text message conversation between Agent Falco and Tex Decker, initiated December 2, 4:31 PM.
What’s your 10-20, Decker?
I’m at the diner on 4th and Gill. Their chicken and waffles are to die for.
Get them to go then. There’s a serial killer on the loose—
The Butcher just claimed a third victim.
Todd wants us both in her office immediately for our assignments.
Roger that, boss.
Tex, I thought we discussed this.
I know, I know. You’re not my boss.
But old habits die hard.
I’ll see you in Todd’s office in 20.
Yeah, okay. 10-4.
Partner.
